docs.snippet: BUENOS AIRES. ARGENTINA'S social revolution, continuously cultivated  by the Peron regime which initiated it, has curiously enough had little effect on the world of books. Through soaring labor costs and dissipation of foreign exchange it has altered...
docs.lead_paragraph: BUENOS AIRES. ARGENTINA'S social revolution, continuously cultivated by the Peron regime which initiated it, has curiously enough had little effect on the world of books. Through soaring labor costs and dissipation of foreign exchange it has altered the actual business of publishing and importing to the point where some of the most successful and venerable houses are weakwith despair. But from a literary standpoint the revolution has yet to make a clear-cut imprint.

docs.lead_paragraph: Alexander McLean Nicolson, a leader in the development of piezoelectric crystals and vacuum tube oscillators in television and radio for the American Telephone and Telegraph Company and the Western Electric Company, died Thursday night at his home, 112 East Seventy-fourth Street, after a long illness. He was 69 years old.
